Items: While not unusual, soiled toilet tissue was the most common litter found. This is a result of the recreational beach use traffic this year being 'out of control' and upwards of 400+ persons at the beach on a hot summer day. Carters Beach is proposed to be designated by the Province for a Nature Reserve but its primary public use (due to its extensive white sand beaches and aqua blue almost Caribbean like waters) is for recreation. Both the Province and the local municipality are dragging their feet in providing basic amenities such as washrooms, adequate garbage collection receptacles or environmental education signage to support the heavy visitor use. As a result, the Carters Beach Cleanup had to deal with cleaning up the remnants of extreme outdoor bathroom use behind the dunes of the beach. Other related litter such as clothing, diapers and beer bottles were also common place.

I offered your data sheets to one of the Parks and People volunteers who was able to attend, but they didn't take them. About a dozen people came to the cleanup, and they collected about 2 dozen bags of trash. It wasn't weighed. No statistics were kept on what was collected. We normally do a cleanup in the spring. It was postponed several times, because of bad weather, and eventually cancelled. Parks Canada suggested we do a fall cleanup and affiliate it with your organization. The volunteers from Parks and People said that there were a lot fewer people than we usually get at a spring cleanup, and that the number of bags of trash collected per person was a lot less than when we do a spring cleanup.
